## let do Dynamic Context Execution
Currently, your TOML templates inject static placeholders like {{args}} and {{code}}. You could make the library exponentially more powerful by extending the Python/Rust parser to evaluate dynamic shell commands or environment variables right before hydration.
Example: Allowing syntax like {{$(git diff)}} or {{env.AWS_REGION}} would let developers pull live system state or infrastructure context directly into the LLM prompt without manually piping it in.
## Model Context Protocol (MCP) Integration
Because PromptOps targets agentic tools, wrapping the library in a lightweight Model Context Protocol (MCP) server would be a game-changer. Instead of developers manually copying prompts or piping them into the terminal, tools like Claude Code could dynamically discover, read, and utilize your entire template library as a native, self-updating resource.
## Expand the Pre-Commit Configuration
You have a .pre-commit-config.yaml in the repository, but as the prompt library grows, you should ensure it includes strict TOML linting (taplo is a great tool for this). Forcing contributors to automatically format and validate their custom prompts locally will save you from having to fix syntax errors during code review.
## Breaking Downstream Workflows (The Pathing Issue)
The Pitfall: By reorganizing the directories (moving prompts to ai-agents, ai-infra, search, etc.), you are introducing breaking changes. Users who have hardcoded paths like commands/prompts/claude-specific.toml into their CI/CD pipelines, bash aliases, or Aider /read commands will experience immediate failures when they pull this update.
The Mitigation: Implement a deprecation strategy rather than a hard cutover.
Add a mapping.json or fallback logic in the CLI/TUI that silently redirects calls from the old paths to the new paths.
Alternatively, keep the old files for one more version release, but replace their contents with a warning message pointing to the new file location.
## The "Agnostic" Dilution Trap
The Pitfall: The PR replaces Claude-specific terminology with "generic agent terms." While this makes the library universally compatible, it risks stripping away the unique operational advantages of specific tools. For example, Claude Code is highly autonomous and can edit multiple files without being micromanaged, whereas a standard web-based LLM might just output a wall of text. A generic prompt might under-utilize a powerful agent or over-complicate a simple chatbot.
The Mitigation: Introduce tool-specific execution flags within your TOML files. For example, add an optional [tool_overrides.claude] block in the TOML that appends specific behavioral instructions only when the user runs the prompt via Claude Code.
