## TOML String Escaping (Prompt Injection)
The Pitfall: Your prompts are wrapped in multi-line TOML strings ("""). If a user runs pop use <tool> --args @file.py and the target Python file happens to contain """ (like a standard Python docstring), it will prematurely terminate the TOML string during parsing or hydration, instantly crashing the CLI or Rust TUI.
The Mitigation: Ensure both your Python and Rust parsing logic explicitly sanitizes or escapes triple quotes in the injected {{args}} and {{code}} payloads before attempting to construct the final string.
## Dual-Client Feature Drift
The Pitfall: The project currently maintains a Python CLI (promptops) and a Rust TUI (promptops-tui). As you add complex features (like the new common/security.toml mappings mentioned in the PR), keeping the parsing logic, fuzzy searching, and variable injection identical across two entirely different programming languages will become a massive maintenance burden. Bugs will appear in the Rust version that don't exist in Python, and vice versa.
The Mitigation: Pick one core engine (likely Rust for performance) to handle all the actual file parsing and hydration logic, and compile it as a binary. The Python CLI should just be a lightweight wrapper that calls the Rust binary, rather than maintaining its own separate TOML parsing logic.
